# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agronomy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The **ABC model of flower development** is a scientific model of the process by which flowering plants produce a pattern of gene expression in meristems that leads to the appearance of an organ oriented towards sexual reproduction, a flower.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The latter phase has been modelled using the **ABC model**, which aims to describe the biological basis of the process from the perspective of molecular and developmental genetics.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] An external stimulus is required in order to trigger the differentiation of the meristem into a flower meristem.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This stimulus will activate mitotic cell division in the apical meristem, particularly on its sides where new primordia are formed.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This same stimulus will also cause the meristem to follow a developmental pattern that will lead to the growth of floral meristems as opposed to vegetative meristems.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The main difference between these two types of meristem, apart from the obvious disparity between the objective organ, is the verticillate (or whorled) phyllotaxis, that is, the absence of stem elongation among the successive whorls or verticils of the primordium.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] These verticils follow an acropetal development, giving rise to sepals, petals, stamens and carpels.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Another difference from vegetative axillary meristems is that the floral meristem is "determined", which means that, once differentiated, its cells will no longer divide.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The identity of the organs present in the four floral verticils is a consequence of the interaction of at least three types of gene products, each with distinct functions.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] According to the ABC model, functions A and C are required in order to determine the identity of the verticils of the perianth and the reproductive verticils, respectively.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] These functions are exclusive and the absence of one of them means that the other will determine the identity of all the floral verticils.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B function allows the differentiation of petals from sepals in the secondary verticil, as well as the differentiation of the stamen from the carpel on the tertiary verticil.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Goethe's **foliar theory** was formulated in the 18th century and it suggests that the constituent parts of a flower are structurally modified leaves, which are functionally specialized for reproduction or protection.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The transition from the vegetative phase to a reproductive phase involves a dramatic change in the plant's vital cycle, perhaps the most important one, as the process must be carried out correctly in order to guarantee that the plant produces descendants.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This transition is characterised by the induction and development of the meristem of the inflorescence, which will produce a collection of flowers or one flower.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This morphogenetic change contains both endogenous and exogenous elements: For example, in order for the change to be initiated the plant must have a certain number of leaves and contain a certain level of total biomass.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Certain environmental conditions are also required such as a characteristic photoperiod.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Plant hormones play an important part in the process, with the gibberellins having a particularly important role.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are many signals that regulate the molecular biology of the process.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The following three genes in *Arabidopsis thaliana* possess both common and independent functions in floral transition: *FLOWERING LOCUS T* (*FT*), *LEAFY* (*LFY*), *SUPPRESSOR OF OVEREXPRESSION OF CONSTANS1* (*SOC1*, also called *AGAMOUS-LIKE20*).
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] *SOC1* is a MADS-box-type gene, which integrates responses to photoperiod, vernalization and gibberellins.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The meristem can be defined as the tissue or group of plant tissues that contain undifferentiated stem cells, which are capable of producing any type of cell tissue.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Their maintenance and development, both in the vegetative meristem or the meristem of the inflorescence is controlled by genetic cell fate determination mechanisms.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that a number of genes will directly regulate, for example, the maintenance of the stem cell's characteristics (gene *WUSCHEL* or *WUS*), and others will act via negative feedback mechanisms in order to inhibit a characteristic (gene *CLAVATA* or *CLV*).
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this way both mechanisms give rise to a feedback loop, which along with other elements lend a great deal of robustness to the system.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Along with the *WUS* gene the *SHOOTMERISTEMLESS* (*STM*) gene also represses the differentiation of the meristematic dome.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This gene acts by inhibiting the possible differentiation of the stem cells but still allows cell division in the daughter cells, which, had they been allowed to differentiate, would have given rise to distinct organs.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] A flower's anatomy, as defined by the presence of a series of organs (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels) positioned according to a given pattern, facilitate sexual reproduction in flowering plants.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model of flower development was first formulated by George Haughn and Chris Somerville in 1988.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was first used as a model to describe the collection of genetic mechanisms that establish floral organ identity in the Rosids, as exemplified by *Arabidopsis thaliana*, and the Asterids, as demonstrated by *Antirrhinum majus*.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both species have four verticils (sepals, petals, stamens and carpels), which are defined by the differential expression of a number of homeotic genes present in each verticil.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This means that the sepals are solely characterized by the expression of A genes, while the petals are characterized by the co-expression of A and B genes.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The B and C genes establish the identity of the stamens and the carpels only require C genes to be active.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Type A and C genes are reciprocally antagonistic.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The fact that these homeotic genes determine an organ's identity becomes evident when a gene that represents a particular function, for example the A gene, is not expressed.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* this loss results in a flower which is composed of one verticil of carpels, another containing stamens and another of carpels.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This method for studying gene function uses reverse genetics techniques to produce transgenic plants that contain a mechanism for gene silencing through RNA interference.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In other studies, using forward genetics techniques such as genetic mapping, it is the analysis of the phenotypes of flowers with structural anomalies that leads to the cloning of the gene of interest.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The flowers may possess a non-functional or over expressed allele for the gene being studied.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The existence of two supplementary functions, D and E, have also been proposed in addition to the A, B and C functions already discussed.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function D specifies the identity of the ovule, as a separate reproductive function from the development of the carpels, which occurs after their determination.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Function E relates to a physiological requirement that is a characteristic of all floral verticils, although, it was initially described as necessary for the development of the three innermost verticils (Function E *sensu stricto*).
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, its broader definition (*sensu lato*) suggests that it is required in the four verticils.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The gene products of genes with D and E functions are also MADS-box genes.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The methodology for studying flower development involves two steps.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Firstly, the identification of the exact genes required for determining the identity of the floral meristem.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* these include APETALA1 (*AP1*) and LEAFY (*LFY*).
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Secondly, genetic analysis is carried out on the aberrant phenotypes for the relative characteristics of the flowers, which allows the characterization of the homeotic genes implicated in the process.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] There are a great many mutations that affect floral morphology, although the analysis of these mutants is a recent development.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Supporting evidence for the existence of these mutations comes from the fact that a large number affect the identity of floral organs.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] For example, some organs develop in a location where others should develop.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is called homeotic mutation, which is analogous to HOX gene mutations found in *Drosophila*.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Arabidopsis* and *Antirrhinum*, the two taxa on which models are based, these mutations always affect adjacent verticils.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Cloning studies have been carried out on DNA in the genes associated with the affected homeotic functions in the mutants discussed above.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] These studies used serial analysis of gene expression throughout floral development to show patterns of tissue expression, which, in general, correspond with the predictions of the ABC model.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The nature of these genes corresponds to that of transcription factors, which, as expected, have analogous structures to a group of factors contained in yeasts and animal cells.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This group is called MADS, which is an acronym for the different factors contained in the group.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] These MADS factors have been detected in all the vegetable species studied, although the involvement of other elements involved in the regulation of gene expression cannot be discounted.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, function A is mainly represented by two genes *APETALA1* (*AP1)* and *APETALA2* (*AP2*) *AP1* is a MADS-box type gene, while *AP2* belongs to the family of genes that contains AP2, which it gives its name to and which consists of transcription factors that are only found in plants.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] AP2 has also been shown to complex with the co-repressor TOPLESS (TPL) in developing floral buds to repress the C-class gene *AGAMOUS* (*AG*).
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] *AP2* not only functions in the first two verticils, but also in the remaining two, in developing ovules and even in leaves.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] It is also likely that post-transcriptional regulation exists, which controls its A function, or even that it has other purposes in the determination of organ identity independent of that mentioned here.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Antirrhinum*, the orthologous gene to *AP1* is *SQUAMOSA* (*SQUA*), which also has a particular impact on the floral meristem.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs for *AP2* are *LIPLESS1* (*LIP1*) and *LIPLESS2* (*LIP2*), which have a redundant function and are of special interest in the development of sepals, petals and ovules.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] A total of three genes have been isolated from *Petunia hybrida* that are similar to *AP2*: *P. hybrida APETALA2A* (*PhAP2A*), *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] *PhAP2A* is, to a large degree, homologous with the *AP2* gene of *Arabidopsis*, both in its sequence and in its expression pattern, which suggests that the two genes are orthologs.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The proteins *PhAP2B* and *PhAP2C*, on the other hand, are slightly different, even though they belong to the family of transcription factors that are similar to *AP2*.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition they are expressed in different ways, although they are very similar in comparison with *PhAP2A*.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In fact, the mutants for these genes do not show the usual phenotype, that of the null alleles of A genes.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana* the type-B function mainly arises from two genes, *APETALA3* (*AP3*) and *PISTILLATA* (*PI*), both of which are MADS-box genes.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] A mutation of either of these genes causes the homeotic conversion of petals into sepals and of stamens into carpels.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This also occurs in its orthologs in *A. majus*, which are DEFICIENS (*DEF*) and *GLOBOSA* (*GLO*) respectively.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] For both species the active form of binding with DNA is that derived from the heterodimer: AP3 and PI, or DEF and GLO, dimerize.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This is the form in which they are able to function.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *GLO*/*PI* lines that have been duplicated in *Petunia* contain *P. hybrida GLOBOSA1* (*PhGLO1*, also called *FBP1*) and also *PhGLO2* (also called *PMADS2* or *FBP3*).
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] For the functional elements equivalent to *AP3*/*DEF* in *Petunia* there is both a gene that possesses a relatively similar sequence, called *PhDEF* and there is also an atypical B function gene called PhTM6.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic studies have placed the first three within the «euAP3» lineage, while PhTM6 belongs to that of «paleoAP3».
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] As discussed above, the floral organs of eudicotyledonous angiosperms are arranged in 4 different verticils, containing the sepals, petals, stamen and carpels.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The ABC model states that the identity of these organs is determined by the homeotic genes A, A+B, B+C and C, respectively.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In contrast with the sepal and petal verticils of the eudicots, the perigone of many plants of the family Liliaceae have two nearly identical external petaloid verticils (the tepals).
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In order to explain the floral morphology of the Liliaceae, van Tunen *et al.* proposed a modified ABC model in 1993.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This model suggests that class B genes are not only expressed in verticils 2 and 3, but also in 1.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] It therefore follows that the organs of verticils 1 and 2 express class A and B genes and this is how they have a petaloid structure.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] This theoretical model has been experimentally proven through the cloning and characterization of homologs of the *Antirrhinum* genes *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* in a Liliaceae, the tulip *Tulipa gesneriana*.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are expressed in verticils 1,2 and 3.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The homologs *GLOBOSA* and *DEFICIENS* have also been isolated and characterized in *Agapanthus praecox* ssp.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] *orientalis* (Agapanthaceae), which is phylogenetically distant from the model organisms.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In this study the genes were called *ApGLO* and *ApDEF*, respectively.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Both contain open reading frames that code for proteins with 210 to 214 amino acids.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Phylogenetic analysis of these sequences indicated that they belong to B gene family of the monocotyledons.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In situ hybridization studies revealed that both sequences are expressed in verticil 1 as well as in 2 and 3.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] When taken together, these observations show that the floral development mechanism of *Agapanthus* also follows the modified ABC model.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *A. thaliana*, the C function is derived from one MADS-box type gene called *AGAMOUS* (*AG*), which intervenes both in the establishment of stamen and carpel identity as well as in the determination of the floral meristem.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Therefore, the *AG* mutants are devoid of androecium and gynoecium and they have petals and sepals in their place.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In addition, the growth in the centre of the flower is undifferentiated, therefore the petals and sepals grow in repetitive verticils.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The *PLENA* (*PLE*) gene is present in *A. majus*, in place of the *AG* gene, although it is not an ortholog.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] However, the *FARINELLI* (*FAR*) gene is an ortholog, which is specific to the development of the anthers and the maturation of pollen.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] In *Petunia*, *Antirrhinum* and in maize the C function is controlled by a number of genes that act in the same manner.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The genes that are closer homologs of *AG* in *Petunia* are *pMADS3* and *floral-binding protein 6* (*FBP6*).
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The D function genes were discovered in 1995.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are MADS-box proteins and they have a function that is distinct from those previously described, although they have a certain homology with C function genes.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] These genes are called *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN7* (*FBP7*) and *FLORAL BINDING PROTEIN1L* (*FBP1l*).
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] It was found that, in *Petunia*, they are involved in the development of the ovule.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] Equivalent genes were later found in *Arabidopsis*, where they are also involved in controlling the development of carpels and the ovule and even with structures related to seed dispersal.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The appearance of interesting phenotypes in RNA interference studies in *Petunia* and tomato led, in 1994, to the definition of a new type of function in the floral development model.
[src:agronomy/abc-model-of-flower-development] The E function was initially thought to be only involved in the development of the three innermost verticils, however, subsequent work found that its expression was required in all the floral verticils.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:agronomy/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Aerobiologists have traditionally been involved in the measurement and reporting of airborne pollen and fungal spores as a service to those with allergies.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] However, aerobiology is a varied field, relating to environmental science, plant science, meteorology, phenology, and climate change.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] The first mention of "aerobiology" was made by Fred Campbell Meier in the 1930s.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] The particles, which can be described as Aeroplankton, generally range in size from nanometers to micrometers which makes them challenging to detect.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Aerosolization is the process of small and light particles becoming suspended in moving air.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Now bioaerosols, these pollen and fungal spores can be transported across an ocean, or even travel around the globe.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Due to the high quantities of microbes and the ease of dispersion, Martinus Beijerinck once said "Everything is everywhere, the environment selects".
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] This means that aeroplankton are everywhere and have been everywhere, and it solely depends on environmental factors to determine which remain.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Aeroplankton are found in significant quantities even in the Atmospheric boundary layer (ABL).
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] The effects on climate and cloud chemistry of these atmospheric populations is still under review.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] NASA and other research agencies are studying how long these bioaerosols can remain afloat and how they can survive in such extreme climates.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] The conditions of the upper atmosphere are similar to the climate on Mars' surface, and the microbes found are helping redefine the conditions which can support life.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] The process of dispersal of aerobiological particles has 3 steps: removal from source, dispersion through air, and deposition to rest.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] The particle geometry and environment affect all three phases, however once it is aerosolized, its fate depends on the laws of physics governing the motion of the air.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Pollen and spores can be blown from their surface or shaken loose.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Generally the wind speed required for release is higher than average wind speed.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Some fungi can even be triggered by environmental factors to actively eject spores.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Once released from rest, the aeroplankton is at the mercy of the wind and physics.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] The settling speed of spores and pollen vary and is a major factor in dispersion; the longer the particle is floating, the longer it can be caught by a turbulent wind gust.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Wind speed and direction fluctuate with time and height, so the specific path of once neighboring particles can vary significantly.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] The concentration of particles in the air decreases with distance from source, and the dispersion distance is most accurately modeled as a power function.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Deposition is a combination of gravity and inertia.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] The fall speed for small particles can be calculated by mass and geometry, but the complex shapes of pollen and spores often fall slower than their estimated speed modeled with simple shapes.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Spores can also be removed from the air from impact; the inertia of the particles will cause them to hit surfaces along their path, instead of flowing around them like air.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] There have been many studies performed to understand real-life dispersal patterns of pollen and spores.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] To collect samples, studies often use a volumetric spore trap such as a Hirst-type sampler.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Particles stick to a sampling strip and then can be inspected under a microscope.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Scientists have to count the particles under magnification, and then analyze sample DNA by Amplicon sequence variant (ASV) or another common method.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] A challenge repeatedly cited in literature is that because of differing testing or analysis methodologies, results are not always comparable across studies.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Therefore, extensive data collection must be performed in each study to get an accurate model.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Unfortunately there is no database of aerobiological particle distribution to compare results to.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Allergic rhinitis is a type of inflammation in the nose that occurs when the immune system overreacts to allergens in the air.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] It is typically triggered in humans by pollen and other bioaerosols.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Between 10% and 30% of people in Western countries are affected.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Symptoms are usually worse during pollination periods, when there is significantly more pollen aerosolized in the air.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] In these peak periods, staying indoors is one way to limit exposure.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] However, studies have shown that there are still significant levels of pollen indoors.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] In the winter, pollen levels indoors actually exceed outdoor levels.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Up to date data on pollen levels is critical for humans that have allergies.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] A current limitation is that many spore traps require scientists to identify and count individual pollen grains under magnification.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] This causes data to be delayed, sometimes by over a week.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] There are currently a number of fully automatic spore traps in development, and once they are fully functional they will improve the lives of people with allergies.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Scientists have predicted that the meteorological results of climate change will weaken pollen and spore dispersal barriers, and lead to less biological uniqueness in different regions.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Precipitation increases richness (number of species) of biodiversity in regions because clouds formulate in the upper atmosphere where there is more varied biodiversity.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Specifically in the Arctic, climate change has dramatically increased precipitation, and scientists have seen new microbes in the area because of it.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] Rising summer temperatures and CO2 levels have shown to increase total amounts of pollen released by certain trees, as well as delay the start of pollen season.
[src:agronomy/aerobiology] However, more studies are needed to see long term effects of climate change.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The fundamental principle of aeroponic growing entails suspending plants in a closed or semi-closed environment whilst spraying their dangling roots and lower stems with a nutrient-rich water solution in an atomized or sprayed form.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The upper portion of the plant, including the leaves and crown, referred to as the canopy, extends above.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The plant support structure keeps the roots separated.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] To minimize labor and expenses, closed-cell foam is often compressed around the lower stem and inserted into an opening in the aeroponic chamber.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In the case of larger plants, trellising is employed to support the weight of the vegetation and fruits.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The goal is to maintain an environment free from pests and diseases, allowing the plants to thrive and grow faster than those cultivated in a growing medium.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] However, since most aeroponic environments are not completely sealed off from the outside, pests and diseases can still pose a threat.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Controlled environments facilitate the advancement of plant development, health, growth, flowering, and fruiting for various plant species and cultivars.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Due to the sensitivity of root systems, aeroponics is often combined with conventional hydroponics.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] High-pressure aeroponics refers to the method of delivering nutrients to the roots using mist heads with a size range of 20-50 micrometers.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This is achieved using a high-pressure diaphragm pump operating at around 80 pounds per square inch (550 kPa).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Air cultures maximize air exposure to facilitate optimal plant growth.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The materials and devices that hold and support aeroponically grown plants must be completely free from disease or pathogens.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] A vital characteristic of a genuine aeroponic culture and apparatus is minimal plant support features.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This design allows maximum airflow around the plant by minimizing contact between the plant and the support structure.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In long-term aeroponic cultivation, it is crucial to ensure that the root systems are unconstrained, allowing unrestricted growth, root expansion, unhindered access to pure water, adequate air exchange, and disease-free conditions.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Adequate oxygen (O2) availability in the rhizosphere (root zone) is essential for promoting healthy plant growth.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In aeroponics, where plants are grown in an environment of air and micro-droplets of water, almost any plant can thrive and reach maturity with an abundant supply of oxygen, water, and nutrients.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Some growers prefer aeroponic systems over other hydroponic methods, since the increased aeration of the nutrient solution provides greater oxygenation to the plant roots, stimulating growth and aiding in the prevention of pathogen formation.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Clean air plays a crucial role in purifying the environment for plants in aeroponics.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Unrestricted access to air is necessary for natural plant growth and successful physiological development.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] If the support structure restricts the plant's natural growth, it can increase the risk of plant damage and subsequent disease formation.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Researchers have utilized aeroponics to study the impact of gas composition in the root zone on plant performance.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Soffer and Burger (1988) conducted a study on the effects of dissolved oxygen concentrations in a system they termed "aero-hydroponics," which involved a 3-tier hydro and aero system with distinct zones within the root area.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Their results indicated that dissolved oxygen is crucial for root formation.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Additionally, they found that in the misted section, where nutrient mist was provided, the number and length of roots were consistently greater compared to the submerged or un-misted sections.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Even at the lowest oxygen concentration tested, the misted section demonstrated successful root development.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics also entails the management of CO2 levels in the system's air, which subsequently impacts the rate of photosynthesis in plants.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Utilizing artificial lights for growth offers advantages such as increased growth rates and enhanced reliability compared to solar lighting.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This lighting method can be effectively combined with aeroponics to optimize plant growth.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics offers the advantage of limiting disease transmission since it reduces plant-to-plant contact, and each spray pulse can be kept sterile.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In contrast, diseases can easily spread throughout soil, aggregate, or other growing media, affecting multiple plants.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Traditional greenhouses often require sterilization of solid media after each crop, and sometimes these media are simply discarded and replaced with fresh, sterile ones.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] One significant benefit of aeroponic technology is the ability to quickly remove a diseased plant from the plant support structure without disrupting or infecting other plants, thanks to the isolated nature of the system.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Due to the disease-free environment unique to aeroponics, many plants can be grown at higher densities (plants per square meter) compared to more traditional cultivation methods like hydroponics, soil, and Nutrient Film Technique (NFT).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Commercial aeroponic systems incorporate hardware features that accommodate the expanding root systems of crops.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Researchers have highlighted aeroponics as a valuable, simple, and rapid method for preliminary screening of genotypes for resistance to specific seedling blights or root rots.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The isolating nature of aeroponic systems enables researchers to avoid complications encountered when studying these infections in soil cultures.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponic equipment employs sprayers, misters, foggers, or other devices to create a fine mist of solution for delivering nutrients to plant roots.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponic systems are typically closed-looped systems designed to provide macro and micro-environments that sustain reliable and consistent air cultures.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Several inventions have been developed to facilitate aeroponic spraying and misting.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The size of the water droplet is critical for root development in an aeroponic environment.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In commercial applications, a 360° hydro-atomizing spray is used, which utilizes air pressure misting to cover large areas of roots.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] A variation of the mist technique, known as fogponics, utilizes ultrasonic foggers to mist nutrient solutions in low-pressure aeroponic devices.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Water droplet size plays a vital role in maintaining aeroponic growth.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Water droplets that are too large can limit the availability of oxygen to the root system.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Conversely, excessively fine water droplets generated by ultrasonic misters can lead to excessive root hair growth without developing a lateral root system necessary for sustained growth in an aeroponic system.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Mineralization of ultrasonic transducers requires maintenance and presents a potential risk of component failure.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This is also a drawback of metal spray jets and misters.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Restricted access to water can cause plants to lose turgidity and wilt.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] NASA has provided funding for research and development of new advanced materials aimed at improving the reliability and reducing maintenance in aeroponics.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] It has been determined that a high-pressure hydro-atomized mist with micro-droplets ranging from 5 to 50 micrometers is necessary for sustained aeroponic growth.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] To ensure long-term growth, the mist system must possess significant pressure to effectively penetrate the dense root system(s).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Achieving repeatability is crucial in aeroponics, and this includes maintaining the appropriate hydro-atomized droplet size.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The degradation of the spray caused by mineralization of mist heads hampers the delivery of the water nutrient solution, resulting in an environmental imbalance within the air culture system.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] To address this issue, special low-mass polymer materials have been developed and are utilized to prevent mineralization in the next generation of hydro-atomizing misting and spray jets.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] These materials help maintain the efficiency and effectiveness of the misting system.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The discrete nature of interval and duration aeroponics allows for the measurement of nutrient uptake over time, even under varying conditions.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Barak et al. conducted a study using an aeroponic system to non-destructively measure water and ion uptake rates in cranberries (Barak, Smith et al.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In their research, the team found that by measuring the concentrations and volumes of input and efflux solutions, they could accurately calculate the nutrient uptake rate.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] To validate their findings, they compared the results with N-isotope measurements.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Once their analytical method was verified, Barak et al. proceeded to gather additional data specific to cranberries.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This included studying diurnal variations in nutrient uptake, examining the correlation between ammonium uptake and proton efflux, and exploring the relationship between ion concentration and uptake.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] These findings highlight the potential of aeroponics not only as a valuable research tool for studying nutrient uptake but also as a means to monitor plant health and optimize crop cultivation in closed environments.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Atomization at pressures exceeding 65 pounds per square inch (450 kPa) increases the bioavailability of nutrients.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Consequently, nutrient strength must be significantly reduced to prevent leaf and root burn.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] It's worth noting the large water droplets in the photo on the right, which indicate that the feed cycle may be too long or the pause cycle too short.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Both scenarios discourage lateral root growth and root hair development.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Optimal results are achieved when feed cycles are as short as possible, with roots remaining slightly damp but never excessively dry.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] A typical feed/pause cycle is less than 2 seconds of feeding followed by approximately 1.5–2 minutes of pause, maintained continuously.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] However, when an accumulator system is incorporated, cycle times can be further reduced to less than approximately 1 second of feeding and around 1 minute of pause.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Shortly after its development, aeroponics emerged as a valuable research tool, providing researchers with a non-invasive method to examine developing roots.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This innovative technology expanded the possibilities for conducting experiments by offering a larger number of parameters and a wider range of experimental conditions.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The precise control over root zone moisture levels and water delivery makes aeroponics particularly well-suited for studying water stress.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Hubick evaluated aeroponics as a means to consistently produce plants with minimal water stress, which can be utilized in drought or flood physiology experiments.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics are a better choice when it comes to investigating root morphology.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The absence of aggregates enables researchers to easily access the entire, intact root structure without causing damage that may occur when removing roots from soils or aggregates.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] It has been observed that aeroponics yields more natural root systems compared to hydroponics.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] An *aeroponic system* refers to the collection of hardware and components designed to support plant growth in an air culture.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] An *aeroponic greenhouse* is a controlled environment structure made of glass or plastic, equipped with the necessary tools to cultivate plants in an air/mist environment.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In most low-pressure aeroponic gardens, the plant roots are suspended above a reservoir of nutrient solution or inside a channel connected to a reservoir.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] A low-pressure pump is used to deliver the nutrient solution either through jets or ultrasonic transducers, and the excess solution then drips or drains back into the reservoir.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] However, as plants mature in these units, it is common for certain sections of the root systems to become dry, which hinders proper nutrient uptake.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] These units typically lack the necessary features to purify the nutrient solution and effectively remove inconsistencies, debris, and harmful pathogens.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Due to their cost constraints, such units are often more suitable for small-scale benchtop growing and for demonstrating the principles of aeroponics.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] High-pressure aeroponic techniques, which employ mist generation through high-pressure pump(s), are commonly employed in the cultivation of high value crops and plant specimens.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The benefits of using this method in horticulture can compensate for the higher setup costs involved.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] High-pressure aeroponic systems incorporate advanced technologies for air and water purification, nutrient sterilization, the utilization of low-mass polymers, and pressurized nutrient delivery systems.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] These features enhance the efficiency and effectiveness of the aeroponic setup.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Commercial aeroponic systems comprise high-pressure device hardware along with biological systems.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The biological systems matrix incorporates various enhancements aimed at extending plant life and promoting crop maturation.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] These commercial aeroponic systems, including the high-pressure devices, are primarily utilized for cultivating high-value crops, enabling multiple crop rotations on a continuous commercial scale.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Advanced commercial systems go a step further by incorporating data gathering, monitoring, analytical feedback, and internet connectivity to various subsystems, enhancing overall efficiency and productivity.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Artsikhovski published an article titled "On Air Plant Cultures" in the journal "Experienced Agronomy." In this article, he introduced his method of conducting physiological studies on root systems by spraying various substances in the surrounding air, which is now known as the aeroponics method.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Artsikhovski designed the first aeroponic systems and demonstrated their effectiveness for plant cultivation.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Carter conducted pioneering research on air culture growing and described a method for growing plants in water vapor to facilitate root examination.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Since 2006, aeroponics has been widely used in agriculture worldwide.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Klotz made an important discovery by misting citrus plants, which facilitated his research on diseases affecting citrus and avocado roots.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Trowel successfully grew apple trees using a spray culture technique.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Went coined the term "aeroponics" to describe the air-growing process.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] He grew coffee plants and tomatoes with air-suspended roots, nourishing them through the application of a nutrient mist to the root section.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The first commercially available aeroponic apparatus was manufactured and brought to market by GTi in 1983.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] At that time, it was named the *Genesis Machine*, inspired by the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] GTi's device featured an open-loop water-driven system controlled by a microchip.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] It delivered a high-pressure hydro-atomized nutrient spray within an aeroponic chamber.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The *Genesis Machine* was designed to be connected to a water faucet and an electrical outlet, providing the necessary resources for operation.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponic culturing has brought about a revolution in cloning (vegetative propagation) of plants.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] It has made the propagation of numerous plants, previously considered difficult or impossible, much easier through stem cuttings in aeroponics.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Delicate hardwoods and cacti, which were sensitive to bacterial infections when propagated through cuttings, can now be successfully propagated in aeroponic systems.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The success of propagation in aeroponics can be attributed to the highly aerated environment around the roots, promoting root hair development (Soffer and Burger, 1988), as well as enhanced root and overall growth due to nutrient supply through the aeroponic system (Santos and Fisher, 2009).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Additionally, the absence of rooting media reduces the risk of root diseases (Mehandru et al., 2014).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics plays a crucial role in propagating plants that have low success rates in vegetative propagation, plants with significant medicinal uses, high-demand plants, and in creating new cultivars of specific plant species.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] For instance, Leptadenia reticulata, an important medicinal plant with low reproductive rates through both seeds and cuttings, has found easier propagation through aeroponics (Mehandru et al., 2014).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics has also contributed to the availability of elm trees, including Ulmus Americana cultivars, which were severely affected by Dutch elm disease (Oakes et al., 2012).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics serves as a more advantageous alternative to the traditional method of using overhead misters (Peterson et al., 2018).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] It boasts a higher success rate compared to overhead misters, which have drawbacks such as the need for large volumes of water, potential unsanitary conditions, uneven misting coverage, and possible leaching of foliar nutrients (Peterson et al., 2018).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In essence, cloning has become easier with the use of aeroponic apparatus, as it initiates faster and cleaner root development through a sterile, nutrient-rich, highly oxygenated, and moist environment (Hughes, 1983).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics has made significant advancements in tissue culture technology, enabling faster plant cloning and reducing the labor-intensive steps associated with traditional tissue culture techniques.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] One of the notable benefits of aeroponics is its ability to eliminate the need for stage I and stage II plantings into soil, which has been a challenge for tissue culture growers.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In tissue culture, plants are initially planted in sterile media (stage I) and then transferred to sterile soil (stage II) before eventually being transplanted to field soil.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This entire process is not only labor-intensive but also prone to disease, infection, and failure.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] By utilizing aeroponics, growers can directly clone and transplant air-rooted plants into field soil.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The aeroponic roots are more resistant to wilting, leaf loss, and transplant shock compared to traditional methods like hydroponics.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Moreover, air-rooted plants tend to be healthier and less susceptible to pathogen infections.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] However, it is important to maintain the root chamber's relative humidity (RH) below 70 °F (21 °C) to prevent the development of issues like fungus gnats, algae, and anaerobic bacteria.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The efforts of GTi in developing an all-plastic aeroponic method and apparatus controlled by a microprocessor have ushered in a new era of artificial life support for plants, allowing them to grow naturally without the use of soil or traditional hydroponics.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In fact, GTi obtained a patent for their innovative aeroponic system in 1985.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics has gained recognition as a time- and cost-saving technique.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The economic application of aeroponics in agriculture is under development in the 21st century.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In 1985, GTi unveiled the second generation of aeroponics hardware, known as the "Genesis Growing System".
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This new apparatus represented a significant advancement in aeroponics technology as it introduced a closed-loop system.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The Genesis Growing System utilized recycled effluent, which was precisely controlled by a microprocessor.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] With this innovation, aeroponics expanded its capabilities to include supporting seed germination, making GTi's system the world's first plant and harvest aeroponic system.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] It is worth noting that many of these early open-loop and closed-loop aeroponic systems continue to operate successfully to this day.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics made its transition from laboratories to the commercial cultivation sector.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In 1966, Bruce Briggs, a pioneer in commercial aeroponics, successfully induced roots on hardwood cuttings through air-rooting.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] He discovered that air-rooted cuttings were more robust and hardened compared to those formed in soil, and concluded that air-rooting was a sound principle.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Briggs also found that air-rooted trees could be transplanted to soil without experiencing transplant shock, which is often observed in hydroponic transplants.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In 1982, Isaac Nir in Israel developed a patent for an aeroponic apparatus that utilized compressed low-pressure air to deliver a nutrient solution to suspended plants held by a perforated layer of plastic foam material styrofoam inside large metal containers.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In 1976, British researcher John Prewer conducted a series of aeroponic experiments in the UK, where lettuces were grown from seed to maturity in 22 days using polyethylene film tubes.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The fog droplets used in these experiments were generated by equipment supplied by Mee Industries of California.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In collaboration with John Prewer, a commercial grower named Kings Nurseries on the Isle of Wight used a different design of aeroponics system in 1984 to grow strawberry plants.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The strawberries flourished, yielding a bountiful crop that was highly appreciated by customers, especially the elderly, who valued the cleanliness, quality, and flavor of the fruit, as well as the convenience of picking it without stooping.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In 1983, Richard Stoner filed a patent for the first microprocessor interface designed to deliver tap water and nutrients into an enclosed aeroponic chamber made of plastic.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Stoner subsequently established several companies dedicated to researching and advancing aeroponic hardware, interfaces, biocontrols, and components for commercial aeroponic crop production.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Stoner's company, Genesis Technology Inc, played a pioneering role in manufacturing, marketing, and applying large-scale closed-loop aeroponic systems in greenhouses for commercial crop production.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In the 1990s, General Hydroponics [Europe] (GHE) attempted to introduce aeroponics to the hobby hydroponics market and introduced the Aerogarden system.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Although the Aerogarden did not meet the criteria of "true" aeroponics as it produced droplets instead of a fine mist, it created a demand for aeroponic growing in the hobby market.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The distinction between mist aeroponics and droplet aeroponics became blurred in the eyes of many.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] However, a UK firm called Nutriculture conducted trials of true mist aeroponics, which showed positive results compared to traditional growing techniques like Nutrient Film Technique (NFT) and Ebb & Flood.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In 1986, Stoner achieved a significant milestone by becoming the first person to successfully market fresh aeroponically grown food to a national grocery chain.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] His accomplishment garnered attention, and he was invited for an interview on NPR, where he highlighted the significance of aeroponics in terms of water conservation, both in modern agriculture and even in space exploration.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Plants had their first encounters with Earth's orbit back in 1960 during two separate missions, namely Sputnik 4 and Discoverer 17 (for a comprehensive review of plant growth in space during the first 30 years, refer to Halstead and Scott, 1990).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The Sputnik 4 mission involved carrying seeds of wheat, pea, maize, spring onion, and *Nigella damascena*, while *Chlorella pyrenoidosa* cells were taken into orbit on the Discoverer 17 mission.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Following these early endeavors, plant experiments were conducted on various missions involving Bangladesh, China, and joint Soviet-American efforts, including Biosatellite II, Skylab 3 and 4, Apollo-Soyuz, Sputnik, Vostok, and Zond.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Initial research findings shed light on how low gravity affected the orientation of roots and shoots (Halstead and Scott, 1990).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Subsequent research delved into investigating the impact of low gravity on plants at different levels, such as organismic, cellular, and subcellular.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] At the organismic level, several species including pine, oat, mung bean, lettuce, cress, and *Arabidopsis thaliana* exhibited decreased seedling, root, and shoot growth under low gravity conditions.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] However, lettuce grown on the Cosmos mission showed the opposite effect, displaying enhanced growth in space (Halstead and Scott, 1990).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Mineral uptake in plants grown in space was also found to be affected.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] For instance, peas grown in space demonstrated increased levels of phosphorus and potassium, while the divalent cations calcium, magnesium, manganese, zinc, and iron exhibited decreased levels (Halstead and Scott, 1990).
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In 1996, Richard Stoner's research on organic disease control (ODC) received funding from NASA.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The goal was to develop a natural liquid biocontrol solution for closed-loop hydroponic systems that could prevent plant diseases and increase yields without the need for pesticides.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] By 1997, NASA conducted biocontrol experiments with Stoner's ODC solution.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The experiments took place using BioServe Space Technologies' GAP technology, which consisted of miniature growth chambers.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Bean seeds were treated with the ODC solution in triplicate experiments conducted aboard the MIR space station, at the Kennedy Space Center, and at Colorado State University under total darkness conditions to eliminate light as a variable.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The focus of the NASA experiment was solely on studying the benefits of the biocontrol.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Results from NASA's enclosed environment bean experiments on the MIR space station and shuttle confirmed that ODC promoted increased germination rates, better sprouting, enhanced growth, and activated natural plant disease mechanisms.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Although initially developed for NASA, ODC is not limited to space applications.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Soil and hydroponics growers can also incorporate ODC into their planting techniques, as it complies with USDA NOP standards for organic farming.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] One notable example of ODC's expansion in agriculture is its application in the cannabis industry.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The ODC product line has been developed specifically for emerging agricultural crops like cannabis.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The active ingredients in the ODC cannabis line include the original chitosan ingredient at a concentration of 0.25%, as well as 0.28% colloidal nitrogen and 0.05% calcium.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In order to enhance the resilience of hydroponic and aeroponic systems against plant diseases and reduce reliance on chemical additives, NASA explores the integration of environmental biocontrols into the design of these systems.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The Advanced Plant Habitat (APA), deployed on the International Space Station (ISS) since 2018, exemplifies this approach.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Equipped with over 180 sensors, the APA optimizes plant growth and health while decreasing the need for chemical additive biocontrols.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The sensors monitor various environmental factors, including lighting intensity, spectrum, and photoperiod, temperature, CO2 levels, relative humidity, irrigation, as well as plant-derived ethylene and volatile organic compound (VOC) scrubbing.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Additionally, the APA features leaf and root zone temperature sensors, root zone moisture sensors, and oxygen concentration meters.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] These environmental controls serve two main purposes in inhibiting plant diseases.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Firstly, they maintain environmental conditions that directly hinder the growth of diseases, fungi, and pests.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] By carefully regulating factors like temperature and humidity, the risk of infections, such as botrytis in leaves, is reduced as the environment becomes less conducive to disease proliferation.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Secondly, these controls create conditions that promote the plant's natural disease prevention mechanisms, indirectly inhibiting the effects of plant diseases.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] For instance, experiments with peppers conducted under blue light conditions have shown increased resilience to powdery mildew.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In 1998, Stoner received funding from NASA to develop a high-performance aeroponic system suitable for use on Earth as well as in space.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Through his research, Stoner demonstrated significant increases in growth rates of lettuce plants cultivated in aeroponic systems compared to other cultivation techniques.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] NASA subsequently adopted many of the aeroponic advancements developed by Stoner.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Research efforts have focused on identifying and developing technologies for rapid plant growth in different gravitational environments.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Low-gravity environments present challenges such as efficient delivery of water and nutrients to plants, as well as the recovery of waste products.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Food production in space also requires addressing issues like water management, minimizing water usage, and reducing system weight.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Additionally, future food production on planetary bodies like the Moon and Mars will involve dealing with reduced gravity environments.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Given the varying fluid dynamics at different levels of gravity, optimizing nutrient delivery systems has been a major focus in developing plant growth systems.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Various nutrient delivery methods are currently employed, both on Earth and in low-gravity environments.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Substrate-dependent methods include traditional soil cultivation, zeoponics, agar, and nutrient-loaded ion exchange resins.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In addition to substrate-dependent approaches, non-soil methods have been developed, including the nutrient film technique, ebb and flow, aeroponics, and others.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Hydroponic systems, with their high nutrient solution throughput, can achieve rapid plant growth.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] However, this necessitates large volumes of water and significant recycling of the solution, which poses challenges for controlling solutions in microgravity conditions.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponic systems use hydro-atomized sprays to deliver nutrients, resulting in minimal water usage, enhanced root oxygenation, and excellent plant growth.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The nutrient solution throughput of aeroponic systems is higher compared to other systems designed for low-gravity environments.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics eliminates the need for substrates and reduces the quantity of waste material that must be managed by other life support systems.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] By removing the substrate requirement, planting and harvesting processes are simplified, automation becomes easier, the weight and volume of expendable materials are reduced, and a potential pathway for pathogen transmission is eliminated.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] These advantages highlight the potential of aeroponic production in microgravity environments and its efficiency in food production for outer space.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In 1999, NASA allocated funding to support the development of an inflatable low-mass aeroponic system (AIS) for high-performance food production in both space and on Earth.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The AIS is a self-contained and self-supporting system designed to deliver nutrients and mist to plant roots in an aeroponic environment.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Its inflatable structure offers the advantage of being lightweight and can be deflated to occupy less volume during transportation and storage.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This current version of AIS represents an improvement over previous designs that utilized rigid structures, which tend to be more costly to manufacture and transport.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] On Earth, the cost of materials and transportation can pose challenges to the economic viability of aeroponic systems for commercial growers.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] However, these challenges become even more pronounced when considering the limitations imposed by payload mass for space transportation.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] To overcome these limitations, NASA has developed specialized materials capable of withstanding the harsh space environment for inflatable habitats and structures.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] These materials, similar to aramid fibers, are currently being utilized in the development of expandable habitats by Bigelow Aerospace.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Successful tests have been conducted in space with one of Bigelow's Expandable Activity Modules, demonstrating the feasibility of such inflatable structures in the space environment.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics possesses numerous characteristics that contribute to its effectiveness and efficiency as a method of plant cultivation.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Plants grown using aeroponics spend 99.98% of their time in the air, with only 0.02% in direct contact with hydro-atomized nutrient solution.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This minimal contact with water allows the roots to efficiently capture oxygen.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Additionally, the hydro-atomized mist plays a significant role in effectively oxygenating the roots.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] A comparison between aeroponics and Nutrient Film Technique (NFT) reveals that aeroponics has a lower nutrient throughput of 1.5 milliliters per minute, in contrast to NFT's 1 liter per minute.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The reduced volume of nutrient throughput in aeroponics leads to a reduction in the overall amount of nutrients required for plant development.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Another advantage of the reduced throughput, particularly relevant for space applications, is the decreased water volume used.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This reduction in water volume not only lightens the weight needed to sustain plant growth but also reduces the buffer volume.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Additionally, the volume of effluent produced by the plants is minimized in aeroponics, resulting in a reduced amount of water that requires treatment for reuse.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The use of relatively small solution volumes in aeroponics, combined with the limited exposure of roots to the hydro-atomized mist, minimizes root-to-root contact and reduces the spread of pathogens among plants.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics provides greater control over the environment surrounding the root zone compared to other plant growth systems like hydroponics.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In aeroponics, the plant roots are not continuously surrounded by any medium.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics offers the flexibility to administer various nutrient solutions to the root zone without the need to flush out previous solutions or matrices.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This high level of control is particularly valuable for studying the impact of different nutrient regimens on specific plant species.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Moreover, aeroponics enables a wider range of growth conditions compared to other nutrient delivery systems.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] For instance, the interval and duration of nutrient sprays can be finely adjusted to meet the specific requirements of a plant species.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This means that the aboveground tissue can experience a different environment from that of the roots.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The design of an aeroponic system enables convenient handling of plants.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This is due to the individual separation of plants and their suspension in the air, free from any matrix that could entrap the roots.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] As a result, harvesting each plant becomes a straightforward task.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Similarly, removing any infected plant is easily done without the risk of uprooting or contaminating nearby plants.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponic systems offer cost-effective advantages compared to other systems.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The reduced volume of solution throughput, as mentioned earlier, translates to lower water and nutrient requirements in the system.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Additionally, the elimination of substrates and the need for many moving parts contribute to cost savings.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics offers a solution to minimize the negative impact of pathogens in seed stocks.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] As previously mentioned, the separation of plants and the absence of a shared growth matrix contribute to this advantage.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Moreover, aeroponics provides an enclosed and controlled environment, making it an ideal system for growing pathogen-free seed stocks.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The enclosed growth chamber, combined with the isolation of plants from each other, serves to prevent initial contamination from external pathogens and limits the spread of any existing pathogens among plants.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponics represents a significant advancement in artificial life support for plants, offering benefits such as non-damaging plant support, efficient seed germination, precise environmental control, and unrestricted growth.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In comparison to traditional agricultural techniques like hydroponics and drip irrigation, which have been in use for decades, aeroponics provides notable improvements in plant cultivation.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Contemporary aeroponic techniques have been extensively researched at NASA's BioServe Space Technologies ( Archived 2018-06-15 at the Wayback Machine ) located on the campus of the University of Colorado in Boulder, Colorado.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This research center focuses on the development and commercialization of aeroponic systems.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Additionally, scientists at Ames Research Center have conducted research on enclosed loop systems, investigating methods for growing food crops in low-gravity environments to support future space colonization efforts.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In 2000, Stoner was granted a patent for his organic disease control biocontrol technology, which enables pesticide-free cultivation in aeroponic systems.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] A notable milestone in aeroponics occurred in 2004 when Ed Harwood, the founder of AeroFarms, invented an innovative aeroponic system that utilizes micro fleece cloth to grow lettuces.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] AeroFarms, leveraging Harwood's patented aeroponic technology, currently operates the largest indoor vertical farm in the world based on its annual growing capacity in Newark, New Jersey.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This state-of-the-art farm employs aeroponic technology to produce and distribute up to two million pounds of pesticide-free leafy greens each year.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Aeroponic bio-pharming is an innovative approach used to cultivate pharmaceutical medicines within plants.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This technology provides complete containment, ensuring that effluents and by-products of biopharma crops are confined within a closed-loop facility.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Neil Reese of South Dakota State University conducted GMO research using aeroponics to grow genetically modified corn.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Reese considers it a significant achievement to successfully grow corn in an aeroponic system for bio-massing.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Previous attempts at growing various types of corn using hydroponics had been unsuccessful.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Through the implementation of advanced aeroponics techniques, Dr.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Reese was able to harvest mature ears of genetically modified corn while effectively containing the corn pollen and spent effluent water, thus preventing their release into the environment.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This containment ensures that the surrounding environment remains free from GMO contamination.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Reese emphasizes that aeroponics offers the potential for economically viable bio-pharming practices, making it a promising avenue for pharmaceutical production.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] In 2006, the Institute of Biotechnology at Vietnam National University of Agriculture, in collaboration with Stoner, established a postgraduate doctoral program focused on aeroponics.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The Agrobiotech Research Center, led by Professor Nguyen Quang Thach, is utilizing aeroponic laboratories to advance Vietnam's minituber potato production for certified seed potato cultivation.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] This development holds significant historical importance as it marks the first time a nation has specifically prioritized aeroponics to bolster its agricultural sector, promote economic growth in farming, meet rising demands, improve food quality, and increase overall production.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] "We have shown that aeroponics, more than any other form of agricultural technology, will significantly improve Vietnam's potato production.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] We have very little tillable land, aeroponics makes complete economic sense to us," affirmed Thach.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The integration of aeroponics in Vietnamese agriculture begins with the production of low-cost, certified disease-free organic minitubers.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] These minitubers then serve as a local supply for farmers engaged in field plantings of seed potatoes and commercial potatoes.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] The adoption of aeroponics will benefit potato farmers by providing them with disease-free seed potatoes grown without the use of pesticides.
[src:agronomy/aeroponics] Importantly, it will also reduce their operational costs and increase their yields, according to Thach.
[src:agronomy/aestivation-botany] Aestivation can be an important taxonomic diagnostic; for example Malvaceae flower buds have valvate sepals, with the exception of the genera *Fremontodendron* and *Chiranthodendron*, which have sometimes been misplaced as a result.
[src:agronomy/aestivation-botany] The terms used to describe aestivation are the same as those used to describe leaf vernation.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Studies of business growth and performance in farming have found that successful agricultural businesses are cost-efficient internally and operate in favourable economic, political, and physical-organic environments.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] They are able to expand and make profits, improve the productivity of land, labor, and capital, and keep their costs down to ensure market price competitiveness.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] It encompasses a broader spectrum through the agribusiness system which includes input supplies, value-addition, marketing, entrepreneurship, microfinancing, and agricultural extension.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In some countries like the Philippines, creation and management of agribusiness enterprises require consultation with registered agriculturists above a certain level of operations, capitalization, land area, or number of animals in the farm.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The word "agribusiness" is a portmanteau of the words *agriculture* and *business.* The earliest known use of the word was in the Volume 155 of the Canadian Almanac & Directory published in 1847.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Their book argued against the New Deal programs of then U.S.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] President Franklin Roosevelt as it led to the increase in agricultural prices.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Davis and Goldberg favored corporate-driven agriculture or large-scale farming to revolutionize the agriculture sector, lessening the dependency on state power and politics.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] They explained in the book that vertically integrated firms within the agricultural value chains have the ability to control prices and where they are distributed.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Goldberg then assisted in the establishment of the first undergraduate program in agribusiness in 1966 at the UP College of Agriculture in Los Baños, Philippines as Bachelor of Science in Agriculture major in Agribusiness.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The program was initially a joint undertaking with the UP College of Business Administration in Diliman, Quezon City until 1975.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Drilon of the University of the Philippines then published the book "*Agribusiness Management Resource Materials*" (1971) which would be the foundation of current agribusiness programs around the world.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In 1973, Drilon and Goldberg further expanded the concept of agribusiness to include support organizations such as governments, research institutions, schools, financial institutions, and cooperatives within the integrated Agribusiness System.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Shultz II (2005) of Loyola University Chicago reframed the definition of agribusiness to emphasize its lack of focus on farm production but towards market centricity and innovative approach to serve consumers worldwide.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Boland defined the unique economic characteristics of agribusiness supply chains from industrial manufacturing and service supply chains.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In 2017, noting the rise of genetic engineering and biotechnology in agriculture, Goldberg further expanded the definition of agribusiness which covers all the interdependent aspects of the food system including medicine, nutrition, and health.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] He also emphasized the responsibility of agribusiness to be environmentally and socially conscious towards sustainability.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Some agribusinesses have adopted the triple bottom line framework such as aligning for fair trade, organic, good agricultural practices, and B-corporation certifications towards the concept of social entrepreneurship.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The term value chain was first popularized in a book published in 1985 by Michael Porter, who used it to illustrate how companies could achieve what he called “competitive advantage” by adding value within their organization.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Subsequently, the term was adopted for agricultural development purposes and has now become very much in vogue among those working in this field, with most bilateral and multilateral aid organisations using it to guide their development interventions.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] At the heart of the agricultural value chain concept is the idea of actors connected along a chain producing and delivering goods to consumers through a sequence of activities.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] However, this “vertical” chain cannot function in isolation and an important aspect of the value chain approach is that it also considers “horizontal” impacts on the chain, such as input and finance provision, extension support and the general enabling environment.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The approach has been found useful, particularly by donors, in that it has resulted in a consideration of all those factors impacting on the ability of farmers to access markets profitably, leading to a broader range of chain interventions.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] It is used both for upgrading existing chains and for donors to identify market opportunities for small farmers.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] An agricultural supply store or agrocenter is an agriculturally-oriented shop where one sells agricultural supplies — inputs required for agricultural production such as pesticides, feed and fertilizers .
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Sometimes these stores are organized as cooperatives, where store customers aggregate their resources to purchase agricultural inputs.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Agricultural supply and the stores that provide it are part of the larger Agribusiness industry.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] A farmworker or farmhand, is someone employed for labor in agriculture.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In labor law, the term "farmworker" is sometimes used more narrowly, applying only to a hired worker involved in agricultural production, including harvesting.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Agricultural work varies widely depending on context, degree of mechanization and crop.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Low wages for farmworkers have been associated with farmworker shortages and delayed adoption of agricultural technology.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Agricultural labor is often affected by the human health impacts of environmental issues related to agriculture, such as health effects of pesticides or exposure to other health challenges such as valley fever.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] To address these environmental concerns and marginal working conditions, many labor rights, economic justice and environmental justice movements have been organized or supported by farmworkers.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Irrigation in agriculture is the practice of applying controlled amounts of water to land to help grow crops, landscape plants, and lawns.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Irrigation has been a key aspect of agriculture for over 5,000 years and has been developed by many cultures worldwide.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Irrigation helps to grow crops, maintain landscapes, and revegetate disturbed soils in dry areas and during times of below-average rainfall.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In addition to these uses, irrigation is also employed to protect crops from frost, suppress weed growth in grain fields, and prevent soil consolidation.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] It is also used to cool livestock, reduce dust, dispose of sewage, and support mining operations.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Drainage, which involves the removal of surface and sub-surface water from a given location, is often studied in conjunction with irrigation.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Irrigation and drainage improvements are not necessarily mutually exclusive.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Often both may be required together to assure sustained high-level production of crops.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] For a discussion of the role of drainage practices in agriculture .
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Several irrigation methods differ in how water is supplied to plants.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Surface irrigation, also known as gravity irrigation, is the oldest form of irrigation and has been in use for thousands of years.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In sprinkler irrigation, water is piped to one or more central locations within the field and distributed by overhead high-pressure water devices.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Micro-irrigation is a system that distributes water under low pressure through a piped network and applies it as a small discharge to each plant.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Micro-irrigation uses less pressure and water flow than sprinkler irrigation.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Drip irrigation delivers water directly to the root zone of plants.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Subirrigation has been used in field crops in areas with high water tables for many years.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] It involves artificially raising the water table to moisten the soil below the root zone of plants.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Irrigation water can come from groundwater (extracted from springs or by using wells), from surface water (withdrawn from rivers, lakes or reservoirs) or from non-conventional sources like treated wastewater, desalinated water, drainage water, or fog collection.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Irrigation can be supplementary to rainfall, which is common in many parts of the world as rainfed agriculture, or it can be full irrigation, where crops rarely rely on any contribution from rainfall.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Full irrigation is less common and occurs only in arid landscapes with very low rainfall or when crops are grown in semi-arid areas outside the rainy season.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The environmental effects of irrigation relate to the changes in quantity and quality of soil and water as a result of irrigation and the subsequent effects on natural and social conditions in river basins and downstream of an irrigation scheme.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The effects stem from altered hydrological conditions resulting from the installation and operation of the irrigation scheme.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Amongst these problems is the depletion of underground aquifers through overdrafting.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Soil can be over-irrigated due to poor distribution uniformity or management wastes water, chemicals, and may lead to water pollution.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Over-irrigation can cause deep drainage from rising water tables, which can lead to irrigation salinity problems, requiring watertable control through some form of subsurface land drainage.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Seed companies produce and sell seeds for flowers, fruits and vegetables to commercial growers and amateur gardeners.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The production of seed is a multibillion-dollar global business, which uses growing facilities and growing locations worldwide.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] While most of the seed is produced by large specialist growers, large amounts are also produced by small growers who produce only one to a few crop types.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The larger companies supply seed both to commercial resellers and wholesalers.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The resellers and wholesalers sell to vegetable and fruit growers, and to companies who package seed into packets and sell them on to the amateur gardener.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Most seed companies or resellers that sell to retail produce a catalog, for seed to be sown the following spring, that is generally published during early winter.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] These catalogs are eagerly awaited by the amateur gardener, as during winter months there is little that can be done in the garden so this time can be spent planning the following year’s gardening.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The largest collection of nursery and seed trade catalogs in the U.S. is held at the National Agricultural Library where the earliest catalogs date from the late 18th century, with most published from the 1890s to the present.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Seed companies produce a huge range of seeds from highly developed F1 hybrids to open pollinated wild species.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] They have extensive research facilities to produce plants with genetic materials that result in improved uniformity and appeal.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] These qualities might include disease resistance, higher yields, dwarf habit and vibrant or new colors.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] These improvements are often closely guarded to protect them from being utilized by other producers, thus plant cultivars are often sold under the company's own name and protected by international laws from being grown for seed production by others.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Along with the growth in the allotment movement, and the increasing popularity of gardening, there have emerged many small independent seed companies.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Many of these are active in seed conservation and encouraging diversity.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] They often offer organic and open pollinated varieties of seeds as opposed to hybrids.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Many of these varieties are heirloom varieties.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The use of old varieties maintains diversity in the horticultural gene pool.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] It may be more appropriate for amateur gardeners to use older (heirloom) varieties as the modern seed types are often the same as those grown by commercial producers, and so characteristics which are useful to them (e.g. vegetables ripening at the same time) may be unsuited to home growing.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] A fertilizer or fertiliser is any material of natural or synthetic origin that is applied to soil or to plant tissues to supply plant nutrients.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Fertilizers may be distinct from liming materials or other non-nutrient soil amendments.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Many sources of fertilizer exist, both natural and industrially produced.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] For most modern agricultural practices, fertilization focuses on three main macronutrients: nitrogen (N), phosphorus (P), and potassium (K) with occasional addition of supplements like rock flour for micronutrients.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Farmers apply these fertilizers in a variety of ways: through dry or pelletized or liquid application processes, using large agricultural equipment, or hand-tool methods.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Historically, fertilization came from natural or organic sources: compost, animal manure, human manure, harvested minerals, crop rotations, and byproducts of human-nature industries (e.g. fish processing waste, or bloodmeal from animal slaughter).
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] However, starting in the 19th century, after innovations in plant nutrition following Justus von Liebig's discoveries, an agricultural industry developed around synthetically created agrochemical fertilizers.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] This transition was important in transforming the global food system towards larger-scale industrial agriculture with large crop yields in monocultures.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The invention of Haber process for producing ammonia for nitrogen in the 20th century combined with amplified chemical production capacity created during World War II led to a boom in using nitrogen fertilizers.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In the latter half of the 20th century, increased use of nitrogen fertilizers (800% increase between 1961 and 2019) has been a crucial component of the increased productivity of conventional food systems as part of the so-called "Green Revolution".
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Fertilizers, especially when applied excessively, can have environmental consequences such as water pollution and eutrophication due to nutrient runoff.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Additionally, the chemical process for creating the fertilizers results in byproducts, including carbon and other emissions.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In some cases contamination and pollution of soil result by accumulation of heavy metals contained in some fertilizers collected through mining.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Sustainable agricultural practices, such as reduced tillage and planting buffer strips, can minimize these adverse environmental effects.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] A farm (also called an agricultural holding) is an area of land that is devoted primarily to agricultural processes with the primary objective of producing food and other crops; it is the basic facility in food production.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The name is used for specialized units such as arable farms, vegetable farms, fruit farms, dairy, pig and poultry farms, and land used for the production of natural fiber, biofuel, and other biobased products.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] It includes ranches, feedlots, orchards, plantations and estates, smallholdings, and hobby farms, and includes the farmhouse and agricultural buildings as well as the land.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In modern times, the term has been extended to include such industrial operations as wind farms and fish farms, both of which can operate on land or at sea.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] There are about 570 million farms in the world, most of which are small and family-operated.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Small farms with a land area of fewer than 2 hectares operate on about 12% of the world's agricultural land, and family farms comprise about 75% of the world's agricultural land.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Modern farms in developed countries are highly mechanized.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In the United States, livestock may be raised on rangeland and finished in feedlots, and the mechanization of crop production has brought about a great decrease in the number of agricultural workers needed.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In Europe, traditional family farms are giving way to larger production units.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In Australia, some farms are very large because the land is unable to support a high stocking density of livestock because of climatic conditions.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In less developed countries, small farms are the norm, and the majority of rural residents are subsistence farmers, feeding their families and selling any surplus products in the local market.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] An agricultural engineer is an engineer with an agriculture background.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Agricultural engineers make the engineering designs and plans in an agricultural project, usually in partnership with an agriculturist who is more proficient in farming and agricultural science.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Primary food processing turns agricultural products, such as raw wheat kernels or livestock, into something that can eventually be eaten.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] This category includes ingredients that are produced by ancient processes such as drying, threshing, winnowing and milling grain, shelling nuts, and butchering animals for meat.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] It also includes deboning and cutting meat, freezing and smoking fish and meat, extracting and filtering oils, canning food, preserving food through food irradiation, and candling eggs, as well as homogenizing and pasteurizing milk.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Contamination and spoilage problems in primary food processing can lead to significant public health threats, as the resulting foods are used so widely.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] However, many forms of processing contribute to improved food safety and longer shelf life before the food spoils.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Commercial food processing uses control systems such as hazard analysis and critical control points (HACCP) and failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA) to reduce the risk of harm.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Secondary food processing is the everyday process of creating food from ingredients that are ready to use.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Baking bread, regardless of whether it is made at home, in a small bakery, or in a large factory, is an example of secondary food processing.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Fermenting fish and making wine, beer, and other alcoholic products are traditional forms of secondary food processing.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Sausages are a common form of secondary processed meat, formed by comminution (grinding) of meat that has already undergone primary processing.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Most of the secondary food processing methods known to humankind are commonly described as cooking methods.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Agricultural marketing covers the services involved in moving an agricultural product from the farm to the consumer.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] These services involve the planning, organizing, directing and handling of agricultural produce in such a way as to satisfy farmers, intermediaries and consumers.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Numerous interconnected activities are involved in doing this, such as planning production, growing and harvesting, grading, packing and packaging, transport, storage, agro- and food processing, provision of market information, distribution, advertising and sale.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Effectively, the term encompasses the entire range of supply chain operations for agricultural products, whether conducted through *ad hoc* sales or through a more integrated chain, such as one involving contract farming.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] A farmers' market (or farmers market according to the AP stylebook, also farmer's market in the Cambridge Dictionary) is a physical retail marketplace intended to sell foods directly by farmers to consumers.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Farmers' markets may be indoors or outdoors and typically consist of booths, tables or stands where farmers sell their produce, live animals and plants, and sometimes prepared foods and beverages.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Farmers' markets exist in many countries worldwide and reflect the local culture and economy.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The size of the market may be just a few stalls or it may be as large as several city blocks.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Due to their nature, they tend to be less rigidly regulated than retail produce shops.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] They are distinguished from public markets, which are generally housed in permanent structures, open year-round, and offer a variety of non-farmer/non-producer vendors, packaged foods and non-food products.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Agricultural extension is the application of scientific research and new knowledge to agricultural practices through farmer education.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The field of 'extension' now encompasses a wider range of communication and learning activities organized for rural people by educators from different disciplines, including agriculture, agricultural marketing, health, and business studies.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Extension practitioners can be found throughout the world, usually working for government agencies.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] They are represented by several professional organizations, networks and extension journals.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Agricultural extension agencies in developing countries receive large amounts of support from international development organizations such as the World Bank and the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] An agricultural cooperative, also known as a farmers' co-op, is a producer cooperative in which farmers pool their resources in certain areas of activities.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Agricultural production cooperatives include collective farms in former socialist countries, the kibbutzim in Israel, collectively-governed community shared agriculture, Longo Maï cooperatives in Costa Rica, France, and some other countries, CPAs in Cuba, and Nicaraguan production cooperatives.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In Southeast Asian developing countries such as Vietnam, agricultural cooperatives remain to play an important role in economic and social activities in rural areas, although they have relied mainly on government subsidies .
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Notable examples of agricultural cooperatives include Dairy Farmers Of America, the largest dairy company in the US, Amul, the largest food product marketing organization in India, and Zen-Noah, a federation of agricultural cooperatives that handles 70% of the sales of chemical fertilizers in Japan.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Agricultural cooperatives are owned and democratically controlled by their members.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The governance structure can vary between the different types, but in general members elect representatives to a board of directors and contribute to organizational decision making through a democratic voting process.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) is a specialized agency of the United Nations that leads international efforts to defeat hunger and improve nutrition and food security.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Its Latin motto, *fiat panis*, translates to "let there be bread".
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] It was founded on 16 October 1945 in Quebec City, Canada.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The FAO comprises 194 members, including 193 countries and one member organization, the European Union (EU).
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Its headquarters is in Rome, Italy, and it maintains regional and field offices worldwide, operating in over 130 countries.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] It helps governments and development agencies coordinate their activities to improve and develop agriculture, forestry, fisheries, and land and water resources.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] It also conducts research, provides technical assistance to projects, operates educational and training programs, and collects agricultural output, production, and development data.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The FAO is governed by a biennial conference representing each member country and the EU, which elects a 49-member executive council.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] of China, serves as the chief administrative officer.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Various committees govern matters such as finance, programs, agriculture, and fisheries.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Obverse: Young woman with braid facing left.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Reverse: Cow nursing calf, face value & date.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] An agriculturist, agriculturalist, agrologist, or agronomist (abbreviated as agr.) is a professional in the science, practice, and management of agriculture and agribusiness.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] It is a regulated profession in Canada, Pakistan, India, Japan, the Philippines, the United States, and the European Union.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Other names used to designate the profession include agricultural scientist, agricultural manager, agricultural planner, agriculture researcher, or agriculture policy maker.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The primary role of agriculturists are in leading agricultural projects and programs, usually in agribusiness planning or research for the benefit of farms, food, and agribusiness-related organizations.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Agriculturists usually are designated in the government as public agriculturists serving as agriculture policymakers or technical advisors for policy making.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Preparation of technical engineering designs and construction for agriculture meanwhile are reserved for agricultural engineers.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Agriculturists may pursue environmental planning and focus on agricultural and rural planning.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Studies of agribusiness often come from the academic fields of agricultural economics and management studies, sometimes called agribusiness management.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] To promote more development of food economies, many government agencies support the research and publication of economic studies and reports exploring agribusiness and agribusiness practices.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Some of these studies are on foods produced for export and are derived from agencies focused on food exports.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] These agencies include the Foreign Agricultural Service (FAS) of the U.S.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Department of Agriculture, Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada (AAFC), Austrade, and New Zealand Trade and Enterprise (NZTE).
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] The Federation of International Trade Associations publishes studies and reports by FAS and AAFC, as well as other non-governmental organizations on its website.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In their book *A Concept of Agribusiness*, Ray Goldberg and John Davis provided a rigorous economic framework for the field.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] They traced a complex value-added chain that begins with the farmer's purchase of seed and livestock and ends with a product fit for the consumer's table.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] Agribusiness boundary expansion is driven by a variety of transaction costs.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] As concern over global warming intensifies, biofuels derived from crops are gaining increased public and scientific attention.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] This is driven by factors such as oil price spikes, the need for increased energy security, concern over greenhouse gas emissions from fossil fuels, and support from government subsidies.
[src:agronomy/agribusiness] In Europe and in the US, increased research and production of biofuels have been mandated by law.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Farmers have manipulated plants and animals through selective breeding for decades of thousands of years in order to create desired traits.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] In the 20th century, a surge in technology resulted in an increase in agricultural biotechnology through the selection of traits like the increased yield, pest resistance, drought resistance, and herbicide resistance.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] The first food product produced through biotechnology was sold in 1990, and by 2003, 7 million farmers were utilizing biotech crops.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] More than 85% of these farmers were located in developing countries.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Traditional crossbreeding has been used for centuries to improve crop quality and quantity.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Crossbreeding mates two sexually compatible species to create a new and special variety with the desired traits of the parents.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] For example, the honeycrisp apple exhibits a specific texture and flavor due to the crossbreeding of its parents.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] In traditional practices, pollen from one plant is placed on the female part of another, which leads to a hybrid that contains genetic information from both parent plants.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Plant breeders select the plants with the traits they're looking to pass on and continue to breed those plants.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Note that crossbreeding can only be utilized within the same or closely related species.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Mutations can occur randomly in the DNA of any organism.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] In order to create variety within crops, scientists can randomly induce mutations within plants.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Mutagenesis uses radioactivity to induce random mutations in the hopes of stumbling upon the desired trait.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Scientists can use mutating chemicals such as ethyl methanesulfonate, or radioactivity to create random mutations within the DNA.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Atomic gardens are used to mutate crops.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] A radioactive core is located in the center of a circular garden and raised out of the ground to radiate the surrounding crops, generating mutations within a certain radius.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Mutagenesis through radiation was the process used to produce ruby red grapefruits.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Polyploidy can be induced to modify the number of chromosomes in a crop in order to influence its fertility or size.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Usually, organisms have two sets of chromosomes, otherwise known as a diploidy.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] However, either naturally or through the use of chemicals, that number of chromosomes can change, resulting in fertility changes or size modification within the crop.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Seedless watermelons are created in this manner; a 4-set chromosome watermelon is crossed with a 2-set chromosome watermelon to create a sterile (seedless) watermelon with three sets of chromosomes.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Protoplast fusion is the joining of cells or cell components to transfer traits between species.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] For example, the trait of male sterility is transferred from radishes to red cabbages by protoplast fusion.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] This male sterility helps plant breeders make hybrid crops.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] RNA interference (RNAIi) is the process in which a cell's RNA to protein mechanism is turned down or off in order to suppress genes.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] This method of genetic modification works by interfering with messenger RNA to stop the synthesis of proteins, effectively silencing a gene.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Transgenics involves the insertion of one piece of DNA into another organism's DNA in order to introduce new genes into the original organism.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] This addition of genes into an organism's genetic material creates a new variety with desired traits.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] The DNA must be prepared and packaged in a test tube and then inserted into the new organism.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] New genetic information can be inserted with gene guns/biolistics.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] An example of a gene gun transgenic is the rainbow papaya, which is modified with a gene that gives it resistance to the papaya ringspot virus.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Genome editing is the use of an enzyme system to modify the DNA directly within the cell.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Genome editing is used to develop herbicide resistant canola to help farmers control weeds.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Agricultural biotechnology has been used to improve the nutritional content of a variety of crops in an effort to meet the needs of an increasing population.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Genetic engineering can produce crops with a higher concentration of vitamins.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] For example, golden rice contains three genes that allow plants to produce compounds that are converted to vitamin A in the human body.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] This nutritionally improved rice is designed to combat the world's leading cause of blindness—vitamin A deficiency.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Similarly, the Banana 21 project has worked to improve the nutrition in bananas to combat micronutrient deficiencies in Uganda.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] By genetically modifying bananas to contain vitamin A and iron, Banana 21 has helped foster a solution to micronutrient deficiencies through the vessel of a staple food and major starch source in Africa.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Additionally, crops can be engineered to reduce toxicity or to produce varieties with removed allergens.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] One highly sought after trait is insect resistance.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] This trait increases a crop's resistance to pests and allows for a higher yield.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] An example of this trait are crops that are genetically engineered to make insecticidal proteins originally discovered in (*Bacillus thuringiensis*).
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Bacillus thuringiensis is a bacterium that produces insect repelling proteins that are non-harmful to humans.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] The genes responsible for this insect resistance have been isolated and introduced into many crops.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Bt corn and cotton are now commonplace, and cowpeas, sunflower, soybeans, tomatoes, tobacco, walnut, sugar cane, and rice are all being studied in relation to Bt.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Weeds have proven to be an issue for farmers for thousands of years; they compete for soil nutrients, water, and sunlight and prove deadly to crops.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Biotechnology has offered a solution in the form of herbicide tolerance.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Chemical herbicides are sprayed directly on plants in order to kill weeds and therefore competition, and herbicide resistant crops have to the opportunity to flourish.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Often, crops are afflicted by disease spread through insects (like aphids).
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Spreading disease among crop plants is incredibly difficult to control and was previously only managed by completely removing the affected crop.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] The field of agricultural biotechnology offers a solution through genetically engineering virus resistance.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Developing GE disease-resistant crops now include cassava, maize, and sweet potato.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Agricultural biotechnology can also provide a solution for plants in extreme temperature conditions.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] In order to maximize yield and prevent crop death, genes can be engineered that help to regulate cold and heat tolerance.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] For example, tobacco plants have been genetically modified to be more tolerant to hot and cold conditions, with genes originally found in Carica papaya.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Other traits include water use efficiency, nitrogen use efficiency and salt tolerance.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Quality traits include increased nutritional or dietary value, improved food processing and storage, or the elimination of toxins and allergens in crop plants.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Currently, only a small number of genetically modified crops are available for purchase and consumption in the United States.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] The USDA has approved soybeans, corn, canola, sugar beets, papaya, squash, alfalfa, cotton, apples, and potatoes.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] GMO apples (arctic apples) are non-browning apples and eliminate the need for anti-browning treatments, reduce food waste, and bring out flavor.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] The production of Bt cotton has skyrocketed in India, with 10 million hectares planted for the first time in 2011, resulting in a 50% insecticide application reduction.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] In 2014, Indian and Chinese farmers planted more than 15 million hectares of Bt cotton.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] Agricultural biotechnology regulation in the US falls under three main government agencies: The Department of Agriculture (USDA), the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), and the Food and Drug Administration (FDA).
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] The USDA must approve the release of any new GMOs, EPA controls the regulation of insecticide, and the FDA evaluates the safety of a particular crop sent to market.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] On average, it takes nearly 13 years and $130 million of research and development for a genetically modified organism to come to market.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] The regulation process takes up to 8 years in the United States.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] The safety of GMOs has become a topic of debate worldwide, but scientific articles are being conducted to test the safety of consuming GMOs in addition to the FDA's work.
[src:agronomy/agricultural-biotechnology] In one such article, it was concluded that Bt rice did not adversely affect digestion and did not induce horizontal gene transfer.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] This topic of agronomy involves selective breeding of plants to produce the best crops for various conditions.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Plant breeding has increased crop yields and has improved the nutritional value of numerous crops, including corn, soybeans, and wheat.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] It has also resulted in the development of new types of plants.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] For example, a hybrid grain named triticale was produced by crossbreeding rye and wheat.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Triticale contains more usable protein than does either rye or wheat.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Agronomy has also been instrumental for fruit and vegetable production research.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Furthermore, the application of plant breeding for turfgrass development has resulted in a reduction in the demand for fertilizer and water inputs (requirements), as well as turf-types with higher disease resistance.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Agronomists use biotechnology to extend and expedite the development of desired characteristics.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Biotechnology is often a laboratory activity requiring field testing of new crop varieties that are developed.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] In addition to increasing crop yields agronomic biotechnology is being applied increasingly for novel uses other than food.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] For example, oilseed is at present used mainly for margarine and other food oils, but it can be modified to produce fatty acids for detergents, substitute fuels and petrochemicals.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Agronomists study sustainable ways to make soils more productive and profitable.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] They classify soils and analyze them to determine whether they contain nutrients vital for plant growth.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Common macronutrients analyzed include compounds of nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, calcium, magnesium, and sulfur.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Soil is also assessed for several micronutrients, like zinc and boron.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] The percentage of organic matter, soil pH, and nutrient holding capacity (cation exchange capacity) are tested in a regional laboratory.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Agronomists will interpret these laboratory reports and make recommendations to modify soil nutrients for optimal plant growth.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Additionally, agronomists develop methods to preserve soil and decrease the effects of [erosion] by wind and water.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] For example, a technique known as contour plowing may be used to prevent soil erosion and conserve rainfall.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Researchers of agronomy also seek ways to use the soil more effectively for solving other problems.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Such problems include the disposal of human and animal manure, water pollution, and pesticide accumulation in the soil, as well as preserving the soil for future generations such as the burning of paddocks after crop production.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Pasture management techniques include no-till farming, planting of soil-binding grasses along contours on steep slopes, and using contour drains of depths as much as 1 metre.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Agroecology is the management of agricultural systems with an emphasis on ecological and environmental applications.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] This topic is associated closely with work for sustainable agriculture, organic farming, and alternative food systems and the development of alternative cropping systems.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] Theoretical production ecology is the quantitative study of the growth of crops.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] The plant is treated as a kind of biological factory, which processes light, carbon dioxide, water, and nutrients into harvestable products.
[src:agronomy/agronomy] The main parameters are temperature, sunlight, standing crop biomass, plant production distribution, and nutrient and water supply.
